eye
Homonym Number:
Word Class:noun
Sense Number:2
Definition:[Transf. use of Cornish dial. eye a mass of ore left in a mine to be worked when others are scarce; hence, a `plum', a titbit left to last. cf. OED2 n1 16 b.: AND 1865.] (take) pick the eyes out (of land) to buy or alienate the choicest pieces in a block, to spot. Contrast  gridiron.
Origin:
Register:
Register 2:
Domain:[none]
Region:[none]
See:
Pronunciation:
Notes: (obs. or hist.)
Citations
Date: 0/0/1872
Source: Reminiscences
Author: JOLLIE
Vol / Page: 39
Edition:
Quote:  [To Jollie's account [c1856] of buying the best parts out of a rented or leased run to preventsomeone else stepping in and buying the run near hanmer, A.J. Allom notes: This was probably about the beginning of the grid-iron process of picking the eyes out of country, so much practised afterwards'
Notes: c1872 A.J. Allom's note to Jollie Reminiscences 1841-1865The database also has: 1907 July A.J. Allom's marginal note in 1841-1865 E.Jollie Reminiscences (1878) (MS;ATB) 39 [Allom made the note when he borrowed the MS from Jollie's wife, and made this comment on Jollie's account of buying the best parts out of a run in 1856] This was probably about the beginning of the grid-iron process of picking the eyes out of the country, so much practised afterwards.

